---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="About — Last Page" active="about">
  <div class="static-wrap">
    <h1 class="static-title">About</h1>
    <div class="static-body">

      <p>
        I write. Not because someone asked me to, not because there is a career in it,
        but because I look at the world and I cannot stay quiet. I watch, I read, I think,
        and then the pen moves. That is the whole story.
      </p>

      <p>
        I am a student of literature. I was a lecturer, once. I won't say more about that.
        Some stones you don't turn over in public. What I'll say is that books never failed me
        the way life did. Kafka, Keats, Camus. They've been better company than most rooms
        I've sat in.
      </p>

      <p>
        By the world's measure, I am a failure. I won't argue. But I am not broken by it.
        I need a book, a laptop, a pen, and enough to eat. That is not poverty of spirit.
        That is clarity.
      </p>

      <p>
        I am a communist by heart. Not a slogan, not an aesthetic. A genuine rage at a world
        where the man painting the hoarding sixty feet in the air is told he took no risk,
        and the man who signed the cheque is called the brave one. I don't carry a flag.
        I carry a grief. I want a world that means something, not this well-decorated slavery
        we've agreed to call freedom.
      </p>

      <p>
        I believe in the blind poet, the deaf musician, the dead preacher. John Lennon.
        Jesus, not the God, the man. Read him properly. Karl Marx. Buddha. Einstein. Tesla.
        The fallen ones, the forgotten ones, the ones who were broken lifting something heavy
        so others could walk lighter. Even the fictional ones. Yes, even Batman, even Kakashi.
        You can learn courage from anywhere that offers it.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm a Liverpool fan. I walk alone. I've always known I don't.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm mostly off social media. I check Twitter and Reddit when the world demands to be
        heard, but I left the rest behind. Especially the reels, the shorts, the infinite
        scroll that turns the mind into wallpaper. My phone is an afterthought.
        My laptop is my second heart.
      </p>

      <p>
        I imagine the world Lennon dreamed. I sit sometimes in the Octopus' Garden.
        I read. I write. I watch football. I watch history rhyme.
      </p>

      <p>
        That's me. Welcome, if you're here.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Last Page?</h2>

      <p>
        Think about the last page of a book. Not the last chapter, not the epilogue.
        The very last page. The one you turn to hoping there is something more, one more line,
        one more sentence, and there isn't. Or sometimes there is, and that surprises you.
        That page is where everything lands. The grief, the joy, the relief, the emptiness.
        You've carried the whole book to this point and now it is over and you just sit with it.
      </p>

      <p>
        That is what this site is. Everything here is a last page of something. A thought
        that had to end somewhere. An essay that ran out of road. A feeling that needed
        to be written down before it disappeared. You are either happy or sad at a last page,
        rarely in between. I like that honesty. I wanted to live in it.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Ozymandias IV?</h2>

      <p>
        Two reasons, and they crash into each other perfectly.
      </p>

      <p>
        The first is Shelley. "My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings. Look on my works, ye Mighty,
        and despair." And around him, nothing. Just sand. The man built monuments to his own
        greatness and the desert swallowed all of it. That poem has lived in me since I first
        read it. The arrogance of permanence. The joke the world plays on everyone who believes
        they will last. Every word I write knows it might end up in that desert too. I write
        anyway. Maybe that's the only honest thing to do.
      </p>

      <p>
        The second is Breaking Bad. If you've seen the episode, you know. Walter White
        in the desert, that same poem, that same ruin. A man who believed in his own legend
        and watched it collapse. There is something true in that image that I keep returning to.
        Greatness is fragile. Ego is sand.
      </p>

      <p>
        As for the IV, that is embarrassingly simple. When I went to register the name,
        Ozymandias was taken. So was Ozymandias I, II, and III. I ended up at IV,
        rolled my eyes, and kept it. Sometimes the most accidental things stick the hardest.
        I am Ozymandiasiv now. Online, O IV. A king who couldn't even get his name
        on the first try. The desert approves.
      </p>

      <p>
        I live in Pune. I read a lot. If something here resonates,
        leave a comment or find me on X or Reddit.
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
